<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="app1-reading" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>APP-1 Reading</title>
    <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Things you should understand and know:
        <ul>
            <li>Recognize a vector field in a plane or space</li>
            <li>The difference between a radial and a rotational vector field</li>
            <li>Describe the flux and circulation of a vector field</li>
            <li>What it means to be a simple closed curve</li>
            <li>Define connected and simply connected regions</li>
            <li>What the Fundamental Theorem for Line Integrals says</li>
            <li>What it means for a vector field to be conservative</li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>Things you should be able to do:
        <ul>
            <li>Sketch a vector field from a given equation</li>
            <li>Calculate a scalar line integral along a curve</li>
            <li>Calculate a vector line integral along an oriented curve in space</li>
            <li>Compute the work done in moving an object along a curve in a vector field</li>
            <li>Find a potential function for a conservative vector field</li>
            <li>Use the Fundamental Theorem for Line Integrals to evaluate a line integral in a vector field</li>
            <li>Test a vector field to determine if it is conservative</li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>You will be assessed on the following criteria:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
              that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
          <li><p>Vector Fields: Recognize and sketch vector fields in two and three dimensions. 
            Determine normal and tangential components of vector fields. Compute Gradient fields. 
            Solve applied problems using vector fields.</p></li>
          <li><p>Line Integrals: Define line integrals of a function over a smooth curve. Evaluate 
            line integrals in two and three dimensions. Solve applied problems using line integrals.</p></li>
            <li><p>Conservative Vector Fields: Test for conservative vector fields. Find potential functions. 
            Evaluate line integrals using both direct calculation of parametric descriptions and the Fundamental 
            Theorem for line integrals. Calculate line integrals of vector fields on closed curves. Solve applied 
            problems using conservative vector fields.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>
        <p>All of the readings for this course come from the OpenStax Calculus 
            Volume 3 textbook, which is available for free online at 
            <url href="https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3">
                https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3</url>. You 
                can read the textbook online or download a PDF version. 
                The textbook is also available in print from various retailers 
                if you prefer a physical copy.</p> 
        <p>For this lesson, you should read sections <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/6-1-vector-fields">
            6.1 Vector Fields</url>, <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/6-2-line-integrals">
            6.2 Line Integrals</url>, and <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/6-3-conservative-vector-fields">
            6.3 Conservative Vector Fields</url>. You should read through the sections carefully, 
            making sure to understand the definitions, examples, and key ideas. 
            You should also work through the exercises at the end of each section 
            to test your understanding and practice applying the concepts. Some of the 
            exercises at the end of the section are assigned in the WP assignments.</p>      
</worksheet>
